<div class="content_well top">
	<div class="the_hub_content_wrapper the_hub_article">
		<div class="the_hub_content">
		<a href="/category/the-hub/" class="header_link">
		<div class="the_hub_title_wrapper">
			<div class="the_hub_logo">
				<img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/plugins/lb-content-widgets/img/lit-horn.svg">
			</div>
			<div class="the_hub_title">
				<h1>The Hub</h1>
			</div>
			<div class="the_hub_slogan">
				<h1>News, Notes, Talk</h1>
			</div>
		</div>
		</a>
		
				<div class="the_hub_item">
			<div class="banner_img">
				<a href="https://lithub.com/samantha-schweblin-lydia-davis-angela-flournoy-21-new-books-out-today/" title="Samantha Schweblin! Lydia Davis! Angela Flournoy! 21 new books out today.">
		    		<img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/222658339.jpeg" alt="" class="post_ft entry_post"/>
		    	</a>
			</div>
			
			<div class="post_content">
				<h1 data-report-url="/samantha-schweblin-lydia-davis-angela-flournoy-21-new-books-out-today/"><a href="https://lithub.com/samantha-schweblin-lydia-davis-angela-flournoy-21-new-books-out-today/">Samantha Schweblin! Lydia Davis! Angela Flournoy! 21 new books out today.</a></h1>
				
				<div class="author_info">
					<div class="author_photo"><img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/IMG_0692-1-100x100.jpg" width="100" height="100" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/IMG_0692-1-300x300.jpg 2x" alt="Julia Hass" class="avatar avatar-100 wp-user-avatar wp-user-avatar-100 alignnone photo" /></div>
					<div class="author_name">By&nbsp;<a href="https://lithub.com/author/juliahass/" itemprop="url"><span itemprop="name">Julia&nbsp;Hass</span></a></div>
					<div class="author_hr"><hr/></div>
					<div class="publish_date">September 16, 2025, 4:44am</div>
				</div>
				
				<p>As summer gives way to fall—cooler nights, busier days—there are more opportunities to be present, to be deliberate, to be enmeshed in the dailiness of one&#8217;s life. All of which means&#8230; more time for books! And we have a great haul this week, as ever, including debut novels by Sam Sussman and Angela Flournoy, a memoir about deafness and voice by Rachel Kolb, and a history of the constitution by none other than Jill Lepore. There&#8217;s a primer on the long history of conflict between Israel and Palestine, a new guide to birding, and a creative memoir by Lydia Davis. The three going to the top of my list: Sam Sussman, Angela Flournoy, and Kate Zambreno.</p>
<p>Happy Tuesday, and enjoy the new bounty!</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">*</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="259169" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/samantha-schweblin-lydia-davis-angela-flournoy-21-new-books-out-today/screen-shot-2025-09-02-at-4-30-25-pm/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Screen-Shot-2025-09-02-at-4.30.25-PM.png" data-orig-size="1042,1454" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Animal Stories, Kate Zambreno" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Screen-Shot-2025-09-02-at-4.30.25-PM-215x300.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Screen-Shot-2025-09-02-at-4.30.25-PM-734x1024.png" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-259169" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Screen-Shot-2025-09-02-at-4.30.25-PM-215x300.png" alt="Animal Stories, Kate Zambreno" width="215" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Screen-Shot-2025-09-02-at-4.30.25-PM-215x300.png 215w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Screen-Shot-2025-09-02-at-4.30.25-PM-734x1024.png 734w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Screen-Shot-2025-09-02-at-4.30.25-PM-768x1072.png 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Screen-Shot-2025-09-02-at-4.30.25-PM-43x60.png 43w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Screen-Shot-2025-09-02-at-4.30.25-PM-36x50.png 36w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Screen-Shot-2025-09-02-at-4.30.25-PM.png 1042w" sizes="(max-width: 215px) 100vw, 215px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Kate Zambreno, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9798893380200" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Animal Stories</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Transit)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;Zambreno&#8217;s lucid writing and relentless inquisitiveness shine.&#8221;<br />
—<em>Publishers Weekly</em></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255890" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/attachment/222683966/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/222683966.jpg" data-orig-size="467,700" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Samanta Schweblin, tr. Megan McDowell, Good and Evil and Other Stories" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/222683966-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/222683966.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-255890" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/222683966-200x300.jpg" alt="Samanta Schweblin, tr. Megan McDowell, Good and Evil and Other Stories" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/222683966-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/222683966-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/222683966-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/222683966.jpg 467w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Samanta Schweblin, trans. by Megan McDowell, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780593803103" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Good and Evil and Other Stories</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Knopf)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;No one writes like Samanta Schweblin. Her narratives are sui generis—wonderfully unpredictable and invitingly strange.&#8221;<br />
—Lorrie Moore</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="259172" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/samantha-schweblin-lydia-davis-angela-flournoy-21-new-books-out-today/91cogcq8zl-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/91coGcQ8ZL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="667,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Boy From the North Country, Sam Sussman" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/91coGcQ8ZL._UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/91coGcQ8ZL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-259172" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/91coGcQ8ZL._UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg" alt="Boy From the North Country, Sam Sussman" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/91coGcQ8ZL._UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/91coGcQ8ZL._UF10001000_QL80_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/91coGcQ8ZL._UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/91coGcQ8ZL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 667w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Sam Sussman, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780593835050" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Boy From the North Country</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Penguin Press)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;A debut novel of rare power, a page-turning story of a son learning to return to his mother’s transformative love. Tragic and redemptive, poetic and provocative, this novel held me breathless at every turn. Sussman is a writer of many gifts.&#8221;<br />
—Maria Semple</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="259174" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/samantha-schweblin-lydia-davis-angela-flournoy-21-new-books-out-today/ftsaln-hires-scaled/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/FTSALN-HiRes-scaled-1.jpeg" data-orig-size="1684,2560" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="For the Sun After Long Nights, Fatemeh Jamalpour" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/FTSALN-HiRes-scaled-1-197x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/FTSALN-HiRes-scaled-1-674x1024.jpeg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-259174" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/FTSALN-HiRes-scaled-1-197x300.jpeg" alt="For the Sun After Long Nights, Fatemeh Jamalpour " width="197" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/FTSALN-HiRes-scaled-1-197x300.jpeg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/FTSALN-HiRes-scaled-1-674x1024.jpeg 674w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/FTSALN-HiRes-scaled-1-768x1168.jpeg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/FTSALN-HiRes-scaled-1-39x60.jpeg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/FTSALN-HiRes-scaled-1-1010x1536.jpeg 1010w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/FTSALN-HiRes-scaled-1-1347x2048.jpeg 1347w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/FTSALN-HiRes-scaled-1-33x50.jpeg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/FTSALN-HiRes-scaled-1.jpeg 1684w" sizes="(max-width: 197px) 100vw, 197px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Fatemeh Jamalpour and Nilo Tabrizy, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780593701447" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>For the Sun After Long Nights: The Story of Iran&#8217;s Women-Led Uprising</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Pantheon)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;In a project undertaken at great personal risk, the authors’ compiled historical context, frank personal reflection, and conscientious recordkeeping constitute a critically important &#8216;first rough draft&#8217; of a significant moment being ignored in real time &#8230; Personally driven, historically necessary, and politically salient.&#8221;<br />
—<em>Kirkus</em></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="259173" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/samantha-schweblin-lydia-davis-angela-flournoy-21-new-books-out-today/attachment/9780593241028/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9780593241028.jpeg" data-orig-size="300,450" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="House of Smoke, John T. Boyne" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9780593241028-200x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9780593241028.jpeg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-259173" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9780593241028-200x300.jpeg" alt="House of Smoke, John T. Boyne" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9780593241028-200x300.jpeg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9780593241028-40x60.jpeg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9780593241028-33x50.jpeg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9780593241028.jpeg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>John T. Edge, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780593241028" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>House of Smoke: A Southerner Goes Searching for Home</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Crown)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">“John T. Edge refuses to allow himself or the reader the comfort of spectacle here. He does that Mississippi work and creates a lush, self-reflexive Southern monument that will last forever.&#8221;<br />
—Kiese Laymon</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="259176" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/samantha-schweblin-lydia-davis-angela-flournoy-21-new-books-out-today/screen-shot-2025-09-02-at-4-56-54-pm/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Screen-Shot-2025-09-02-at-4.56.54-PM.png" data-orig-size="978,1456" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Surviving Paris, Robin Allison Davis" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Screen-Shot-2025-09-02-at-4.56.54-PM-202x300.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Screen-Shot-2025-09-02-at-4.56.54-PM-688x1024.png" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-259176" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Screen-Shot-2025-09-02-at-4.56.54-PM-202x300.png" alt="Surviving Paris, Robin Allison Davis" width="202" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Screen-Shot-2025-09-02-at-4.56.54-PM-202x300.png 202w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Screen-Shot-2025-09-02-at-4.56.54-PM-688x1024.png 688w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Screen-Shot-2025-09-02-at-4.56.54-PM-768x1143.png 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Screen-Shot-2025-09-02-at-4.56.54-PM-40x60.png 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Screen-Shot-2025-09-02-at-4.56.54-PM-34x50.png 34w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Screen-Shot-2025-09-02-at-4.56.54-PM.png 978w" sizes="(max-width: 202px) 100vw, 202px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Robin Allison Davis, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780063353138" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Surviving Paris: A Memoir of Healing in the City of Light</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Amistad)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;[Davis] has persisted, determined to survive and thrive in a place she has grown to love. A frank chronicle of pain and hard-won recovery.&#8221;<br />
—<em>Kirkus</em></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="259180" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/samantha-schweblin-lydia-davis-angela-flournoy-21-new-books-out-today/71ndxjgek5l-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71NDXjgEK5L._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="667,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Articulate, Rachel Kolb" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71NDXjgEK5L._UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71NDXjgEK5L._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-259180" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71NDXjgEK5L._UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg" alt="Articulate, Rachel Kolb" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71NDXjgEK5L._UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71NDXjgEK5L._UF10001000_QL80_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71NDXjgEK5L._UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71NDXjgEK5L._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 667w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Rachel Kolb, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780063375185" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Articulate: A Deaf Memoir of Voice</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Ecco)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;Accessible, fascinating, and heartfelt, this thorough examination of contemporary Deafness moves and edifies in equal measure. It’s required reading.&#8221;<br />
—<em>Publishers Weekly</em></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255897" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/81vnbsmbbql-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81VnBsmBBqL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="662,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Angela Flournoy, The Wilderness" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81VnBsmBBqL._UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81VnBsmBBqL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-255897" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81VnBsmBBqL._UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg" alt="Angela Flournoy, The Wilderness" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81VnBsmBBqL._UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81VnBsmBBqL._UF10001000_QL80_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81VnBsmBBqL._UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81VnBsmBBqL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 662w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Angela Flournoy, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780063318779" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Wilderness </em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Mariner)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;Angela Flournoy is singular in how she renders the complicated solidarity that exists between friends. In <em>The Wilderness</em>, there is deep tenderness, room for the grayer areas of experience, for contradiction, ambivalence and the right to be lost.&#8221;<br />
—Raven Leilani</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="259205" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/samantha-schweblin-lydia-davis-angela-flournoy-21-new-books-out-today/61vt0xx6fll-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/61vT0XX6FLL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="676,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Carole King, Jane Eisner" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/61vT0XX6FLL._UF10001000_QL80_-203x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/61vT0XX6FLL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-259205" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/61vT0XX6FLL._UF10001000_QL80_-203x300.jpg" alt="Carole King, Jane Eisner" width="203" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/61vT0XX6FLL._UF10001000_QL80_-203x300.jpg 203w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/61vT0XX6FLL._UF10001000_QL80_-41x60.jpg 41w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/61vT0XX6FLL._UF10001000_QL80_-34x50.jpg 34w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/61vT0XX6FLL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 676w" sizes="(max-width: 203px) 100vw, 203px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Jane Eisner, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780300259469" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Carole King: She Made the Earth Move</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Yale University Press)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;A robust celebration of a legendary musician.&#8221;<br />
—<em>Publishers Weekly</em></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="259192" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/samantha-schweblin-lydia-davis-angela-flournoy-21-new-books-out-today/71kr7gyaazl-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71Kr7GyaaZL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="652,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Right Place Right Time Ali McNamara" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71Kr7GyaaZL._UF10001000_QL80_-196x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71Kr7GyaaZL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-259192" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71Kr7GyaaZL._UF10001000_QL80_-196x300.jpg" alt="Right Place Right Time Ali McNamara" width="196" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71Kr7GyaaZL._UF10001000_QL80_-196x300.jpg 196w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71Kr7GyaaZL._UF10001000_QL80_-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71Kr7GyaaZL._UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71Kr7GyaaZL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 652w" sizes="(max-width: 196px) 100vw, 196px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Ali McNamara, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781526686183" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Right Place, Right Time</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Bloomsbury)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">“An intriguing, luminous romance.”<br />
—<em>Woman&#8217;s Weekly</em></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="259203" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/samantha-schweblin-lydia-davis-angela-flournoy-21-new-books-out-today/71hha7-4cyl-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71hHa7-4cyL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="662,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="When You Come at the King, Elie Honig" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71hHa7-4cyL._UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71hHa7-4cyL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-259203" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71hHa7-4cyL._UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg" alt="When You Come at the King, Elie Honig" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71hHa7-4cyL._UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71hHa7-4cyL._UF10001000_QL80_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71hHa7-4cyL._UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71hHa7-4cyL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 662w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Elie Honig, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780063447363" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>When You Come at the King: Inside DOJ&#8217;s Pursuit of the President, from Nixon to Trump</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Harper)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;A fascinating, fast-paced insider’s account of the trials and tribulations of the nation’s highest-stakes cases from Watergate to today. In this riveting, deeply reported book, Honig offers unique historical insight and a timely and important look at the future of presidential accountability.”<br />
—Anderson Cooper</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="259193" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/samantha-schweblin-lydia-davis-angela-flournoy-21-new-books-out-today/attachment/9780374617127/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9780374617127-scaled.jpeg" data-orig-size="1707,2560" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Tomorrow is Yesterday, Robert Malley" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9780374617127-200x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9780374617127-683x1024.jpeg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-259193" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9780374617127-200x300.jpeg" alt="Tomorrow is Yesterday, Robert Malley" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9780374617127-200x300.jpeg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9780374617127-683x1024.jpeg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9780374617127-768x1152.jpeg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9780374617127-40x60.jpeg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9780374617127-1024x1536.jpeg 1024w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9780374617127-1366x2048.jpeg 1366w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9780374617127-33x50.jpeg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9780374617127-scaled.jpeg 1707w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Hussein Agha and Robert Malley, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780374617127" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Tomorrow is Yesterday: Life, Death, and the Pursuit of Peace in Israel/Palestine</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(FSG)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">“Beautifully written . . . [Agha and Malley are] two people who have genuinely distinct perspectives on the Israeli-Palestinian conflict, and who have been in the room &#8230; A great book.&#8221;<br />
—Chris Hayes</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="259196" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/samantha-schweblin-lydia-davis-angela-flournoy-21-new-books-out-today/9781644453544_p0_v2_s1200x630/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9781644453544_p0_v2_s1200x630.jpeg" data-orig-size="420,630" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Trigger Warning, Jacinda Townsend" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9781644453544_p0_v2_s1200x630-200x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9781644453544_p0_v2_s1200x630.jpeg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-259196" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9781644453544_p0_v2_s1200x630-200x300.jpeg" alt="Trigger Warning, Jacinda Townsend" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9781644453544_p0_v2_s1200x630-200x300.jpeg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9781644453544_p0_v2_s1200x630-40x60.jpeg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9781644453544_p0_v2_s1200x630-33x50.jpeg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9781644453544_p0_v2_s1200x630.jpeg 420w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Jacinda Townsend, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781644453544" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Trigger Warning</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Graywolf)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;A prescient and powerful work that pushes us towards a deeper understanding of ourselves—it’s a fantastic read.”<br />
—S.A. Cosby,</p>
<p><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="259090" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/?attachment_id=259090" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/calls-may-be-recorded.jpg" data-orig-size="443,600" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="calls may be recorded" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/calls-may-be-recorded-222x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/calls-may-be-recorded.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-259090 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/calls-may-be-recorded-222x300.jpg" alt="calls may be recorded" width="222" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/calls-may-be-recorded-222x300.jpg 222w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/calls-may-be-recorded-44x60.jpg 44w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/calls-may-be-recorded-37x50.jpg 37w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/calls-may-be-recorded.jpg 443w" sizes="(max-width: 222px) 100vw, 222px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Katharina Volckmer, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781953387943" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Calls May Be Recorded</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Two Dollar Radio)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;This book is filled with brilliant dialogue, unexpected turns, some very dirty talk with sudden bursts of hilarity, and then fierce sadness. It exudes dark energy. It is highly original. It gives pleasure on every page.&#8221;<br />
—Colm Tóibín</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="259198" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/samantha-schweblin-lydia-davis-angela-flournoy-21-new-books-out-today/attachment/9781250287595/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9781250287595-scaled.jpeg" data-orig-size="1684,2560" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="The Women&#8217;s Orchestra of Auschwitz, Anne Sebba" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9781250287595-197x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9781250287595-674x1024.jpeg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-259198" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9781250287595-197x300.jpeg" alt="The Women's Orchestra of Auschwitz, Anne Sebba" width="197" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9781250287595-197x300.jpeg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9781250287595-674x1024.jpeg 674w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9781250287595-768x1167.jpeg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9781250287595-39x60.jpeg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9781250287595-1011x1536.jpeg 1011w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9781250287595-1347x2048.jpeg 1347w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9781250287595-33x50.jpeg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/9781250287595-scaled.jpeg 1684w" sizes="(max-width: 197px) 100vw, 197px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Anne Sebba, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781250287595" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Women&#8217;s Orchestra of Auschwitz: A Story of Survival</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(St. Martin&#8217;s Press)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;A vivid account of the experiences of the 40 or so women who briefly came together to make the music that saved their lives. Running through this fine book is Sebba&#8217;s empathy for the impossible moral choices presented to these young women.”<br />
—<em>The Guardian</em></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255894" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/attachment/9780374617370/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374617370-scaled.jpg" data-orig-size="1707,2560" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Adam Nicolson, Bird School: A Beginner in the Wood" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374617370-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374617370-683x1024.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-255894" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374617370-200x300.jpg" alt="Adam Nicolson, Bird School: A Beginner in the Wood" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374617370-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374617370-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374617370-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374617370-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374617370-1024x1536.jpg 1024w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374617370-1365x2048.jpg 1365w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374617370-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374617370-scaled.jpg 1707w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Adam Nicolson, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780374617370" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Bird School: A Beginner in the Wood</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(FSG)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;Elegant and involving. Like one of the nests Nicolson finds on his property, it’s been deftly assembled.”<br />
—<em>The Observer</em></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="259199" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/samantha-schweblin-lydia-davis-angela-flournoy-21-new-books-out-today/81nccew9e8l-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81nccEW9e8L._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="663,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Night People, Mark Ronson" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81nccEW9e8L._UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81nccEW9e8L._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-259199" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81nccEW9e8L._UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg" alt="Night People, Mark Ronson" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81nccEW9e8L._UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81nccEW9e8L._UF10001000_QL80_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81nccEW9e8L._UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/81nccEW9e8L._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 663w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Mark Ronson, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781538741115" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Night People: How to Be a DJ in &#8217;90s New York City</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Grand Central)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;A wondrous snapshot of a bygone New York.&#8221;<br />
—<em>Publishers Weekly</em></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="259201" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/samantha-schweblin-lydia-davis-angela-flournoy-21-new-books-out-today/71uvgdwqll-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71UvgdWqlL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="658,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Replaceable You, Mary Roach" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71UvgdWqlL._UF10001000_QL80_-197x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71UvgdWqlL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-259201" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71UvgdWqlL._UF10001000_QL80_-197x300.jpg" alt="Replaceable You, Mary Roach" width="197" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71UvgdWqlL._UF10001000_QL80_-197x300.jpg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71UvgdWqlL._UF10001000_QL80_-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71UvgdWqlL._UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/71UvgdWqlL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 658w" sizes="(max-width: 197px) 100vw, 197px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Mary Roach, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781324050629" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Replaceable You: Adventures in Human Anatomy</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(W. W. Norton)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">“We are all replaceable to some degree or another&#8230;with the exception of Mary Roach. There is no one and nothing like her—singular, bizarre, dedicated, passionate, fascinating. Her writing traffics at the unusual intersection of science, storytelling, and humor.&#8221;<br />
—Jason Alexander</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="259204" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/samantha-schweblin-lydia-davis-angela-flournoy-21-new-books-out-today/the-many-mothers-of-dolores-moore-9781668088333_hr/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/the-many-mothers-of-dolores-moore-9781668088333_hr.jpeg" data-orig-size="1400,2113" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="The Many mothers of Dolores Moore, Anika" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/the-many-mothers-of-dolores-moore-9781668088333_hr-199x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/the-many-mothers-of-dolores-moore-9781668088333_hr-678x1024.jpeg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-259204" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/the-many-mothers-of-dolores-moore-9781668088333_hr-199x300.jpeg" alt="The Many mothers of Dolores Moore, Anika " width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/the-many-mothers-of-dolores-moore-9781668088333_hr-199x300.jpeg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/the-many-mothers-of-dolores-moore-9781668088333_hr-678x1024.jpeg 678w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/the-many-mothers-of-dolores-moore-9781668088333_hr-768x1159.jpeg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/the-many-mothers-of-dolores-moore-9781668088333_hr-40x60.jpeg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/the-many-mothers-of-dolores-moore-9781668088333_hr-1018x1536.jpeg 1018w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/the-many-mothers-of-dolores-moore-9781668088333_hr-1357x2048.jpeg 1357w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/the-many-mothers-of-dolores-moore-9781668088333_hr-33x50.jpeg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/the-many-mothers-of-dolores-moore-9781668088333_hr.jpeg 1400w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Anika Fajardo, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781668088333" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Many Mothers of Dolores Moore</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Gallery Books)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;Anika Fajardo&#8217;s charming and poignant new book is a map of loss, motherhood, and magic that welcomes the reader home. There are tender revelations, vivid details and funny moments throughout.&#8221;<br />
—Chantal Acavedo</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255891" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/81lqok5aztl-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81lqok5azTL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="663,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Jill Lepore, We the People: A History of the U.S. Constitution" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81lqok5azTL._UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81lqok5azTL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-255891" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81lqok5azTL._UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg" alt="Jill Lepore, We the People: A History of the U.S. Constitution" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81lqok5azTL._UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81lqok5azTL._UF10001000_QL80_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81lqok5azTL._UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81lqok5azTL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 663w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Jill Lepore, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781631496080" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>We the People: A History of the U.S. Constitution</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Liveright)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">“The noted historian advances the cause of an aggressively, and progressively, malleable set of rules for government &#8230; With the Constitution under daily threat, Lepore&#8217;s outstanding book makes for urgent reading.&#8221;<br />
—<em>Kirkus</em></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="259202" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/samantha-schweblin-lydia-davis-angela-flournoy-21-new-books-out-today/51u5notcgkl-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/51U5notCGkL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="673,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Into the Weeds, Lydia Daivs" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/51U5notCGkL._UF10001000_QL80_-202x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/51U5notCGkL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-259202" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/51U5notCGkL._UF10001000_QL80_-202x300.jpg" alt="Into the Weeds, Lydia Daivs" width="202" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/51U5notCGkL._UF10001000_QL80_-202x300.jpg 202w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/51U5notCGkL._UF10001000_QL80_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/51U5notCGkL._UF10001000_QL80_-34x50.jpg 34w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/51U5notCGkL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 673w" sizes="(max-width: 202px) 100vw, 202px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Lydia Davis, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780300279740" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Into the Weeds</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Yale University Press)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;Intimate revelations, delicately conveyed.&#8221;<br />
—<em>Kirkus</em></p>
